"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533448","Department for Education","false","2016-07-14","<p>The government is wholly committed to ensuring that refugees who are resettled in the UK receive appropriate support and have a positive experience while they remain in the UK. Children with refugee or humanitarian protection status have access to the education system in the same way as citizen children.</p><p>A key factor in the successful integration of children from overseas into UK schools is their access to English language provision. Local authorities can include an ‘English as an additional language’ (EAL) factor in their funding formulae. Funding allocated through this factor forms part of the school’s core budget and it is for school leaders to determine how best to use their whole budget so that all children can reach their full potential.</p><p>Schools will need to demonstrate to Ofsted that any special educational needs of refugee children, as with all other children, are addressed satisfactorily.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-14T16:52:25.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533448/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533448/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-06","Elections: Fraud","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what policies are in place to ensure that refugees face no barriers to assimilation within the education system.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533449","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The issue of education provision for children seeking asylum is an important one and the Home Office makes every effort to ensure that families with children who claim asylum support have access to education at the earliest opportunity.</p><p>To enable access to education, internal checks are in place to triage applications involving children of school age for priority dispersal from initial accommodation facilities into permanent accommodation.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T13:06:49.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533449/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533449/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","Elections: Fraud","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what policies are in place to ensure that newly arrived asylum seekers placed in Home Office initial accommodation have immediate access to the education system.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533450","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-19","<p>Government funding between 2014/15 and 2015/16 to the National Youth Theatre Great Britain, the National Youth Orchestra, the National Youth Dance Company, and the Youth Music Theatre UK is set out in the table. Youth Music Theatre UK and the National Youth Orchestra receive funding as National Youth Music Organisations, which is jointly funded through the Department for Education and Arts Council England lottery money.</p><p> </p><p>These figures include total funding provided through Grant in Aid and Lottery funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>DFE</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>DCMS</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Grant in Aid 2014/15 – 2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Grant in Aid 2014/15 – 2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Lottery Funding 2014/15 – 2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>*Grants for the Arts</strong> <strong>2014/15 – 2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Youth Theatre of Great Britain</p></td><td><p>£611,538</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Youth Orchestra**</p></td><td><p>£500,000</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£44,441</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sadler's Wells Trust Ltd. (National Youth Dance Company specific)***</p></td><td><p>£650,000</p></td><td><p>£200,000</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Youth Music Theatre UK**</p></td><td><p>£300,000</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£37,250</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* Grants for the arts is the Arts Council's Lottery-funded grant programme for individuals, arts organisations and other people who use the arts in their work. Grants are available for activities carried out over a set period and which engage people in England in arts activities and help artists and arts organisations in England carry out their work</p><p>**National Youth Music Organisation funding</p><p>*** The funding is paid to Sadler’s Wells as the grant recipient for use specifically for National Youth Dance Company activities</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-07-19T15:09:28.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533450/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533450/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-06","Absent Voting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding (1) the National Youth Theatre, (2) the National Youth Orchestra, (3) the National Youth Dance Company, and (4) the Youth Music Theatre UK, receive from (a) the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, and (b) the Department for Education.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533451","Department for Education","false","2016-07-13","<p>We want schools to build the skills and expertise required to plan strategically for the provision of careers education and guidance, embedding careers and employability skills in the curriculum and engaging external partners in the delivery of high quality, inspirational support. The careers strategy, to be published later this year, will set out further details of how we will support schools to achieve this. The strategy has been developed in consultation with key partners across the education and careers sectors.</p><p> </p><p>Pupils can gain confidence and motivation from the opportunity to explore career ideas through individual, face-to-face discussions with a range of people. The careers statutory guidance sets out the main qualifications for careers professionals: the Qualification in Career Guidance (QCG) (which replaced the earlier Diploma in Careers Guidance) and the Level 6 Diploma in Career Guidance and Development. The statutory guidance also provides information about the register of careers professionals, developed by the Career Development Institute, which schools can use to search for a career development professional who can deliver a particular service or activity.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-13T16:13:33.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533451/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533451/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-06","Local Government: Yorkshire and the Humber","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what additional qualifications are required to teach Careers Education in schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533452","Department for Education","false","2016-07-14","<p>Sex and relationships education (SRE) is compulsory in all maintained secondary schools and academies are expected to provide SRE as part of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p>Any school teaching SRE must have regard to Secretary of State’s Sex and Relationship Education Guidance (2000). The guidance makes clear that all sex and relationship education should be age-appropriate. Schools have the freedom to decide which topics are most relevant to their pupils to ensure they develop positive values and a moral framework that will guide their decisions, judgments and behaviour.</p><p>To support teaching about healthy relationships, the PSHE Association has developed non-statutory guidance for schools about the topic of consent, which was published in March 2015. We strongly welcome this guidance, which will help teachers clearly establish the legal framework around consent and supports the government’s ‘This is Abuse’ campaign, which helped educate young people about damaging behaviours within relationships. ‘This is abuse’ was followed up this year by the £3.85 million “Disrespect NoBody” campaign, supported by Government Equalities Office and Home Office. The campaign aims to prevent the onset of domestic violence in adults by challenging attitudes and behaviours amongst teenage boys and girls that abuse in relationships is acceptable.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-14T16:53:24.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533452/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533452/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-06","Devolution: Sheffield City Region","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the study by the Universities of Bristol and Central Lancashire which found that 22 per cent of boys aged 14 to 17 have perpetrated acts of sexual coercion or abuse, what sex education initiatives they have in place that are specifically aimed at boys within that age group.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533453","Department for Education","false","2016-07-26","<p>We are pleased that the OECD recognises in their review the changes we have made in recent years to ensure that all young people leave full-time education with a high standard of English.</p><p> </p><p>The primary National Curriculum emphasises the teaching of early reading through systematic phonics and the importance of accurate spelling, punctuation and grammar. At secondary school pupils are expected to read a wide range of texts fluently and with good understanding.</p><p> </p><p>We have reformed GCSEs to ensure they are more stretching and provide greater assurance of core literacy than the old GCSE. We are also taking action to improve the rigour and relevance of English Functional Skills qualifications, which are taken by many students and apprentices aged 16 and over.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure all young people have every opportunity to secure proficiency in English, since 2014 we have required every 16-19 year old not holding a good pass in GCSE English and mathematics to continue to study these subjects as part of their 16-19 study programme. We have also embedded English and mathematics into our work-based training programmes such as apprenticeships and traineeships.</p><p> </p><p>Last summer’s GCSE results show that over 4,000 more students aged 17 and over secured GCSE English at grades A*-C than the previous year.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-26T15:44:20.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533453/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533453/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-06","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to improve teenage literacy, in the light of the 2016 OECD report <i>Building skills for all: A review of England</i>, which stated that the UK has the lowest literacy rates among 16 to 19 year-olds out of 23 developed countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533454","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>The European Court of Justice has held that EU law must be interpreted in the light of the relevant rules of international law and that, as such, under EU law Heads of State enjoy a special status (different from that of all other Union citizens).</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-07-20T10:52:00.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533454/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533454/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-06","Issa Amro","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bridges of Headley on 27 June (HL657), whether the "special status" enjoyed by the Sovereign is granted by EU law.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL1035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533455","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p>I am pleased to say that branches open an extra 200,000 hours a week since the start of the Post Office’s transformation programme and customer satisfaction with the network is high<em>. </em></p><p> </p><p>Management and provision of the Post Office network is the operational responsibility of the Post Office. I have asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the noble Baroness on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-07-11T14:00:11.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533455/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533455/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-06","Israeli Settlements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in each month since May 2005, (1) what was the total size of the Post Office network, and (2) how many post office closures took place.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL1036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533456","Home Office","false","2016-07-19","<p>As the Minister for Preventing Abuse, Exploitation and Crime set out on 28 June::</p><p>https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2016-06-28/debates/16062854000001/IndependentAdvocatesForTraffickedChildren</p><p>The Government is committed to commencing section 48 of the Modern Slavery Act and developing the accompanying secondary legislation and statutory guidance. As part of the commencement process, we will work with interested parties, including Non-Governmental Organisations to determine the scale of the service.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-19T12:18:22.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533456/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533456/answer","Hansard Extract - Independent Advocates for Trafficked Children.doc","Hansard Extract - Independent Advocates for Trafficked Children.doc","Read out of debate - Hansard","Read out of debate - Hansard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533456/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Contracts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how many independent child trafficking advocates will be needed to fulfil the requirements under section 48 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL1039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533457","Home Office","false","2016-07-19","<p>On 7 November, the day that s52 of the Act came into Force, the Government issued full guidance on GOV.UK. A circular providing information to all bodies subject to the duty, including local authority Chief Executives, was sent the next day. Further communications to raise awareness of the Duty to Notify are planned this summer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-19T11:29:03.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533457/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533457/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","European Union (Withdrawal) Bill: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when and how local authority chief executives have been informed about their statutory duty to notify information about suspected victims of slavery or human trafficking under section 52 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL1040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533458","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Home Office Circular on the Modern Slavery Act, along with a list of those to whom it was sent, is available on <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>.</p><p>Human trafficking and modern slavery is covered within the core learning offer for prison and probation staff. Supplementary training on the subject of human trafficking and the exploitation of vulnerable individuals is available to officers working with particularly vulnerable groups, such as foreign national or female offenders.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-07-20T15:59:46.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533458/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533458/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-06","Environment Protection: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guidance has been issued to the Courts and HM Prison Service to ensure that section 45 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 is fully embedded into their training.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL1041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533459","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Lord Chancellor has the power to issue guidance or directions to the Director of Legal Aid casework under section 4 of LASPO. No such guidance or directions have been issued in respect of legal aid available as a result of section 47 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-07-20T14:31:24.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533459/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533459/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-06","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guidance has been provided to the Legal Aid Agency about section 47 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL1042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533460","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>NHS Improvement continues to work with those providers who have not been able to agree control totals by the end of July. At present, 213 of 238 providers (89.5%) have an agreed a control total. Those providers who have been unable to agree a control total will not be able to access the sustainability and transformation fund.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is currently consulting on a new oversight regime, which details proposals on how providers will be monitored in future and this will set out how variance from financial plan or control total will be managed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement does not intend to replace the boards of those providers who do not achieve financial balance by the end of 2016/17. The organisation’s new oversight regime also sets out in detail how it proposes to monitor and support providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Mandate to the NHS 2016-17, a copy of which is attached, confirms that the National Health Service must ensure that it balances its budget, including commissioners and providers living within their budgets. To support this, £1.8 billion of NHS England’s budget for 2016-17 will be allocated through the Sustainability and Transformation Fund to support providers, in particular emergency services, payable through commissioning or as other support.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1044 ; HL1045","2016-07-13T15:06:23.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533460/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533460/answer","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533460/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-06","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many, and what percentage of, NHS providers have signed up to the first round of proposed control totals; and how they plan to respond to those providers who (1) have not signed up, or (2) refuse to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawhinney",,"Lord Mawhinney","HL1043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533461","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>NHS Improvement continues to work with those providers who have not been able to agree control totals by the end of July. At present, 213 of 238 providers (89.5%) have an agreed a control total. Those providers who have been unable to agree a control total will not be able to access the sustainability and transformation fund.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is currently consulting on a new oversight regime, which details proposals on how providers will be monitored in future and this will set out how variance from financial plan or control total will be managed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement does not intend to replace the boards of those providers who do not achieve financial balance by the end of 2016/17. The organisation’s new oversight regime also sets out in detail how it proposes to monitor and support providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Mandate to the NHS 2016-17, a copy of which is attached, confirms that the National Health Service must ensure that it balances its budget, including commissioners and providers living within their budgets. To support this, £1.8 billion of NHS England’s budget for 2016-17 will be allocated through the Sustainability and Transformation Fund to support providers, in particular emergency services, payable through commissioning or as other support.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1043 ; HL1045","2016-07-13T15:06:23.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533461/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533461/answer","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533461/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-06","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the membership of those NHS provider boards that do not achieve financial balance by the end of 2016–17 will be replaced.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawhinney",,"Lord Mawhinney","HL1044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533462","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>NHS Improvement continues to work with those providers who have not been able to agree control totals by the end of July. At present, 213 of 238 providers (89.5%) have an agreed a control total. Those providers who have been unable to agree a control total will not be able to access the sustainability and transformation fund.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is currently consulting on a new oversight regime, which details proposals on how providers will be monitored in future and this will set out how variance from financial plan or control total will be managed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement does not intend to replace the boards of those providers who do not achieve financial balance by the end of 2016/17. The organisation’s new oversight regime also sets out in detail how it proposes to monitor and support providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Mandate to the NHS 2016-17, a copy of which is attached, confirms that the National Health Service must ensure that it balances its budget, including commissioners and providers living within their budgets. To support this, £1.8 billion of NHS England’s budget for 2016-17 will be allocated through the Sustainability and Transformation Fund to support providers, in particular emergency services, payable through commissioning or as other support.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1043 ; HL1044","2016-07-13T15:06:23.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533462/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533462/answer","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHSE_mandate_16-17_22_Jan.pdf","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","NHS England Mandate 2016-17","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533462/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-06","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government by how much they estimate the deficit of NHS providers will have been reduced by the end of the 2016–17.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawhinney",,"Lord Mawhinney","HL1045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533463","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-12","<p>We were disappointed to learn about Médecins Sans Frontières' rejection of EU funding in Sudan. Sudan is a major source, host and transit country for migration. As such we remain committed to tackling the full range of migration issues in Sudan, including addressing the conflicts and the human rights situation, and supporting regional co-operation and efforts to stop people trafficking and smuggling through the ‘Khartoum Process’. Through DFID, we will deliver support that addresses the root causes of migration, and strengthen the basis for inclusive economic development and increased employment opportunities to encourage Sudanese people to better see their future in Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-07-12T16:34:04.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533463/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533463/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-06","Medecins Sans Frontieres: EU Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of Médecins Sans Frontières' rejection of EU funding in Sudan in response to the EU's policies on migrants attempting to reach Europe.","false","Biography information for Lord Chidgey",,"Lord Chidgey","HL1046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533464","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Government is continuing its Chairmanship of the Khartoum Process, and remains committed in its support for human rights. Our focus remains on the implementation of the actions agreed at last year’s EU-Africa Valletta Summit on migration.</p><p>We are working with EU and international partners to ensure that EU funding underlying the Khartoum Process is properly monitored and overseen, including compliance with the EU Treaties which includes respect for human rights.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL1048 ; HL1050","2016-07-14T13:07:37.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533464/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533464/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","Horn of Africa: EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to commit to include safe and legal routes of passage from the Horn of Africa into the Khartoum Process.","false","Biography information for Lord Chidgey",,"Lord Chidgey","HL1047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533465","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Government is continuing its Chairmanship of the Khartoum Process, and remains committed in its support for human rights. Our focus remains on the implementation of the actions agreed at last year’s EU-Africa Valletta Summit on migration.</p><p>We are working with EU and international partners to ensure that EU funding underlying the Khartoum Process is properly monitored and overseen, including compliance with the EU Treaties which includes respect for human rights.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL1047 ; HL1050","2016-07-14T13:07:37.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533465/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533465/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","Horn of Africa: EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role they plan to take in the design of an international migration policy, based on respect for human rights, when they no longer chair the Khartoum Process.","false","Biography information for Lord Chidgey",,"Lord Chidgey","HL1048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533466","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-14","We are aware of, and deeply troubled by, reports of collusion between Sudanese police forces and people smugglers. We have raised our concerns over these reports with both the Ministry of Interior and the Commissioner for Refugees. We will continue to raise our concerns with the Government of Sudan as part of our wider engagement on migration issues.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-14T15:52:09.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533466/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533466/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Sudan: Human Trafficking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports from Human Rights Watch of collusion between Sudanese police forces and people smugglers trafficking people in the region.","false","Biography information for Lord Chidgey",,"Lord Chidgey","HL1049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533467","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Government is continuing its Chairmanship of the Khartoum Process, and remains committed in its support for human rights. Our focus remains on the implementation of the actions agreed at last year’s EU-Africa Valletta Summit on migration.</p><p>We are working with EU and international partners to ensure that EU funding underlying the Khartoum Process is properly monitored and overseen, including compliance with the EU Treaties which includes respect for human rights.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL1047 ; HL1048","2016-07-14T13:07:37.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533467/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533467/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-06","Horn of Africa: EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the monitoring and oversight mechanisms in place in respect of the use of EU funds to ensure that the Khartoum Process complies with human rights norms.","false","Biography information for Lord Chidgey",,"Lord Chidgey","HL1050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535362","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>I have been holding, and will continue to hold, discussions with my international counterparts on the outcome of the EU referendum. Last week I met international counterparts at the NATO summit. I will meet many more overseas counterparts at the Asia–Europe Meeting in Ulaanbaatar later this week. I will also attend the Foreign Affairs Council, which will include an informal dinner on 17 July with my European counterparts to discuss the referendum outcome and an EU and Gulf Cooperation Council Summit Dinner on 18 July.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-07-12T15:47:16.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535362/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535362/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his international counterparts on the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","905831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535363","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","I saw the Chief Minister, Fabian Picardo, yesterday; it was my third such conversation with him since the UK referendum. I have not only recommitted the British Government to the full involvement of Gibraltar in the negotiations for our exit from and subsequent relationship with the EU 27; I have also invited the Chief Minister to identify the key economic priorities for the people of Gibraltar as we approach those negotiations.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-12T16:01:59.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535363/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535363/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Gibraltar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to protect the interests of Gibraltar as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","true","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","905822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535364","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The UK referendum made a decision to leave the EU, not to turn our backs on Europe, let alone the world. Throughout the referendum debate, campaigns on both sides rejected any notion that a “Leave” vote would signal any kind of retreat from the world. The UK will remain a major player, fully engaged in world affairs, including through our membership of multilateral organisations. We are a Permanent member of the UN Security Council; the second largest contributor to NATO; a key member of the Commonwealth, of the G7 and the G20. We also remain committed to renewing the nuclear deterrent. Our voice will always be prominent – but we will perhaps have to work a little bit harder to ensure that our voice carries the same authority it did before.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-07-12T15:44:11.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535364/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535364/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of withdrawal from the EU on the UK's role in global affairs.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","905828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535365","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>We continue to lobby the Iranians regularly about all our consular cases in Iran, including that of Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe. I have raised the case a number of times, and, on 4 July, spoke to Foreign Minister Zarif. I subsequently followed that up with a letter. On 18 May, my hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood), the Minister with responsibility for the Middle East, met Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe’s family. We will continue to push the Iranians for consular access to her—the challenge is that Iran does not recognise dual nationality—and for more information about the charges that are alleged against her.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-07-12T15:48:59.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535365/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535365/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations the UK Government has made to the Iranian authorities on the case of Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","905825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535366","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The dialogue is an important juncture in our relationship and we were invited by Sudan to commence it. Let me make it very clear that we need to continue to support Sudan. It is a source, host and transit country for migration. What is going on there affects the rest of Europe, and so we want to continue to help with the dire humanitarian situation there. Given that 2.5 million people are long-term displaced in Darfur alone, people need our support.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-12T16:15:19.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535366/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535366/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-06","Sudan: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's objectives are for the UK-Sudan strategic dialogue.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","905823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532864","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-13","<p>As set out in our White Paper, “Success as a Knowledge Economy: Teaching Excellence, Social Mobility and Student Choice” we plan to implement the Teaching Excellence Framework (TEF) in stages.</p><ul><li>In Year One all providers with satisfactory quality assessments will automatically achieve a rating of ‘Meets Expectations’.</li><li>Year Two will be a trial year for the full assessment process at provider level. Year Three in will be the first full year of assessments at provider level, and we will also carry out a number of pilots at disciplinary level.</li><li>Year Four will be the first year of disciplinary level assessments and the first year in which post-graduate taught provision may be included.</li></ul><p>Further detail on the timeline for Year Two is set out in the TEF Technical Consultation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-13T09:33:34.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532864/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532864/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Higher Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has for the implementation of the Teaching Excellence Framework.","false","Biography information for Lord Haselhurst","Saffron Walden","Sir Alan Haselhurst","41835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532865","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-08-26","<p>In due course, Britain will be leaving the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. But it would not be appropriate to provide a running commentary on initial discussions with individual countries. My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has established the Department for International Trade to promote British trade across the world and ensure the UK takes advantage of the huge opportunities open to us. We will engage fully with a broad range of stakeholders, including both governments and business over the coming weeks and months as we prepare for the negotiation with the EU and other international partners.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","41849 ; 41850","2016-08-26T13:09:28.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532865/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532865/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532865/answer/previousversion/6533","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions the Government has had with the government of China on a potential free trade agreement between the UK and China.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","41848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532866","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-08-26","<p>In due course, Britain will be leaving the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. But it would not be appropriate to provide a running commentary on initial discussions with individual countries. My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has established the Department for International Trade to promote British trade across the world and ensure the UK takes advantage of the huge opportunities open to us. We will engage fully with a broad range of stakeholders, including both governments and business over the coming weeks and months as we prepare for the negotiation with the EU and other international partners.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","41848 ; 41850","2016-08-26T13:09:28.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532866/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532866/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532866/answer/previousversion/6534","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions the Government has had with the government of India on a potential free trade agreement between the UK and India.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","41849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532867","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-08-26","<p>In due course, Britain will be leaving the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. But it would not be appropriate to provide a running commentary on initial discussions with individual countries. My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has established the Department for International Trade to promote British trade across the world and ensure the UK takes advantage of the huge opportunities open to us. We will engage fully with a broad range of stakeholders, including both governments and business over the coming weeks and months as we prepare for the negotiation with the EU and other international partners.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","41848 ; 41849","2016-08-26T13:09:28.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532867/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532867/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532867/answer/previousversion/6535","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions the Government has had with the US administration on a potential free trade agreement between the UK and the US.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","41850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532868","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-20","<p>My Ministerial colleagues and I, as well as officials from the Department for International Trade, the Department for Exiting the EU and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, are engaging with a wide range of businesses including current and prospective investors.</p><p>Prior to my appointment, BIS Ministers were communicating to these businesses through phone calls, letters, speeches and participation in roundtables and this work continues. We are engaging with businesses and speaking to investors, both in the UK and overseas, to reassure them that Britain is very much open for business.</p><p>We are also working with colleagues in the Cabinet Office, HM Treasury and other key departments to ensure a fully coordinated approach to this work and will continue with our marketing activities to promote Britain as a GREAT place in which to invest and with which to trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-20T13:54:04.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532868/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532868/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-05","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking in response to the outcome of the EU referendum to encourage foreign investment in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532869","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer I gave on 5 July to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-30/41526/" target="_blank">41526</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","41896 ; 41897","2016-07-12T09:51:32.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532869/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532869/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Government has made of the availability outside the UK of experienced trade negotiators to assist the UK in negotiating trade deals with other states.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532870","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer I gave on 5 July to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-30/41526/" target="_blank">41526</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","41895 ; 41897","2016-07-12T09:51:32.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532870/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532870/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate the Government has made of the number of people needed to negotiate replacement trade agreements with (a) the EU and (b) non-EU countries as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532871","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer I gave on 5 July to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-30/41526/" target="_blank">41526</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","41895 ; 41896","2016-07-12T09:51:33.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532871/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532871/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the Government plans to begin recruiting people to negotiate trade deals with the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532872","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>Leaving the EU offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade.</p><p>We have been consulting, and will continue to consult, a broad range of stakeholders, including governments and business, on the implications of the referendum result.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-09-09T13:41:37.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532872/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532872/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what countries the Government has made representations to on negotiating trade deals as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532873","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-14","<p>Increasing the National Living Wage (NLW) for workers aged 25 and over to £17.50 in 2020 would represent an increase of 143% on the current NLW (£7.20) and of 94% on the current forecasted NLW of £9.00 by 2020.</p><p>Based on an underlying assumption that the wage distribution from April 2015 grows in line with the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) average earnings forecast made in March 2016, we estimate that in 2020, a NLW of £17.50 would be equivalent to around 116% of the projected median wage. Around 15 million employees would be covered by such an NLW, and labour costs would be around £150 billion higher in 2020 compared to a counterfactual of forecast average earnings growth (in nominal terms) due to the direct effects of the NLW. This is equivalent to an increase in total compensation of employees of almost 15%.</p><p>We also estimate that there would be somewhere close to 1.75 million job losses and somewhere between 65,000 and 119,000 business deaths. There would also most likely be a substantial reduction in hours worked, increased labour costs and increased prices, and obvious disincentives to starting new businesses.</p><p>This assessment is based on BIS analysis of provisional data from the Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings 2015 and is subject to significant uncertainty given that a National Living Wage of £17.50 is considerably higher than any previous NMW increase or any minimum wage internationally. Our cost estimates do not include estimates of any ripple effects higher up the wage distribution if employers were to restore wage differentials above the NLW.</p>","Bromsgrove","Sajid Javid",,"2016-07-14T10:04:52.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532873/answer","Biography information for Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532873/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Minimum Wage: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will undertake an assessment of the potential effect on business of introducing a minimum wage of £17.50 per hour.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","41917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532874","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>Leaving the EU offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade.</p><p>We have been consulting, and will continue to consult, a broad range of stakeholders, including governments and business, on the implications of the referendum result.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-09-09T13:43:30.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532874/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532874/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-05","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, of which governments states have made official representations to the Government since 24 June 2016 on negotiating a free trade deal with the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532875","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave on 5 July to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-29/41488/" target="_blank">41488</a>.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-11T14:07:10.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532875/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532875/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Answer of 24 May 2016 to Question 37703, when he plans to establish the reading room for hon. Members to access Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership documents.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","41927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532876","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Steel Council met on the 8<sup>th</sup> June to consider initial recommendations from the Council’s four working groups. The industry chaired working groups cover trade, energy, procurement, and future capability and capacity. The secretariat for the Steel Council, comprising of Gareth Stace from UK Steel and senior representatives from the Department of Business, Innovation and Skills, meet on a regular basis to drive this work forward. In the last month, the procurement working group has met twice on the 9<sup>th</sup> and 24<sup>th</sup> June, the trade working group met on the 22<sup>nd</sup> June, and the future capability and capacity working group met on the 7<sup>th</sup> July.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-11T14:21:47.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532876/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532876/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Steel Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on what dates the Steel Council or its sub-working groups have met in the last month.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","41953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532877","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-14","<p>The result of the EU referendum has raised many questions, for all our stakeholders and citizens. However, nothing changes in the immediate term. We will continue taking forward the important legislation that we set before Parliament in the Queen’s Speech, including the Higher Education and Research Bill. We will also continue with our further education reform programme.</p><p>On Friday 8 July we published the Post-16 Skills Plan. This is our long-term, ambitious framework to support young people and adults to secure a lifetime of sustained skilled employment and meet the needs of rapidly changing economy by putting employers in the lead. The reforms set out in the Skills Plan, which are based on the findings an independent expert panel chaired by Lord Sainsbury, are just as critical following the EU referendum result.</p><p>Our priority will be to work with both the further education and higher education sectors to fully understand the impact of the referendum and help shape our approach for higher and further education in the coming months. We will also continue to focus on high quality apprenticeships and remain committed to 3m starts by 2020.</p><p>The employment prospects for our young people are good - the labour market for young people is the strongest it has been for almost 10 years with the employment rate for the 4 million 16-24s not in full-time education being 74.3%.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-14T10:07:00.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532877/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532877/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on (a) education and training opportunities for and (b) future employment prospects of 16 to 20 year olds.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532878","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>My right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-12T09:54:03.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532878/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532878/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-05","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of which policy areas within his Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532879","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that Brexit means Brexit. We must now prepare for the process to leave the EU and the Government is committed to ensuring the best possible outcome for the British people in the negotiations.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-08-02T15:54:10.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532879/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532879/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-05","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of holding a second referendum on the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532880","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Europe Unit will bring together officials and policy expertise from across the Cabinet Office, Treasury, Foreign Office and BIS. It will be based in the Cabinet Office and report to Cabinet on possible mechanisms for delivering the outcome of the referendum, advising on transitional issues and exploring objectively options for our future relationship with Europe and the rest of the world.</p><p> </p><p /><p><br></p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-11T08:11:15.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532880/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532880/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-05","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the remit and composition is of the Cabinet Office unit charged with examining the options and possibilities of negotiating the UK's exit from the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","41926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532881","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Government had a clear position on the referendum and it was right for the civil service to work in support of that. We now have clear instructions from the British people and Government will of course work to take those instructions forward.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-11T08:54:51.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532881/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532881/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-05","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contingency planning the Government undertook in the event of a vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","41894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532882","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Cabinet Office funds NCS through an annual grant agreement with NCS Trust. Each year, an independent evaluation of NCS is published, including information on the total cost of the programme and cost per participant. These evaluations can be found at: <a href="http://www.ncsyes.co.uk/our-impact" target="_blank">http://www.ncsyes.co.uk/our-impact</a> and the 2015 evaluation is due to be published later this year.</p><p>NCS Trust publishes its accounts each year, and information for 2015/16 will be released in due course. As an independent organisation, NCS Trust makes decisions about the breakdown of its annual budget, including on marketing and recruitment.</p><p>Payments to individual regional providers cannot be released for commercial reasons.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-07-12T15:53:06.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532882/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532882/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532882/answer/previousversion/6558","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-05","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much was spent on each young person taking part in the National Citizens Service (NCS) in each of the last three financial years; how much is received by a regional provider to deliver the NCS programme to each young person; how much is spent by the NCS Trust on all activity other than that given to a regional provider to deliver the NCS programme; how much is given to the NCS Trust for each young person to undertake the entirety of NCS-related activity; and how much is spent annually by the NCS Trust on marketing and recruitment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","41906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532883","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-11","<p>Since April 2015, individuals with defined benefit (DB) pensions are legally required to take independent financial advice from an adviser authorised by the Financial Conduct Authority before transferring or taking their savings as a cash lump sum, if the total value of their benefits is above £30,000.</p><p>This requirement reflects the fact that DB pensions offer a high level of security that should not be relinquished without fully understanding the risks of doing so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-11T12:32:37.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532883/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532883/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-05","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's policy is on obtaining pension transfer reports when making transfers from defined benefit schemes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","41840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532884","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-13","<p>The National Infrastructure Delivery Plan, published in March, sets out the government’s infrastructure plan until 2021. It includes plans to empower local leaders to drive growth and shape their communities. Any updates, including relating to legacy planning, would be announced in the usual way at a fiscal event.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-13T09:12:34.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532884/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532884/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-05","Nationally Significant Infrastructure Projects","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what legacy funding he plans to make available to communities in which nationally significant infrastructure projects are located.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","41878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532885","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility will produce a revised forecast for the UK public finances in the autumn, which will take account of the UK’s decision to leave the EU, alongside other developments in the economy and public finances.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-11T08:55:19.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532885/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532885/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-05","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, in what year he predicts the UK will achieve a budget surplus.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532886","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility will produce a revised forecast for the UK public finances in the autumn, which will take account of the UK’s decision to leave the EU, alongside other developments in the economy and public finances.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-11T08:58:37.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532886/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532886/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-05","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate when the Exchequer will next achieve a surplus.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","41937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532887","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-13","<p>While it is clear that we do now face a significant economic challenge as a result of the referendum decision, the UK economy is well placed to respond. We have seen volatility in financial markets following the referendum. However, markets have continued to function effectively throughout and we continue to be in close contact with the Bank of England and the FCA to monitor developments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-13T10:12:32.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532887/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532887/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-05","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on (a) the UK economy, (b) market conditions, (c) projected GDP and (d) likely future trends in the value of the pound.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532888","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for the UK’s future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements for this. In the meantime, my department continues working to deliver the government’s agenda, and take forward the legislation that we set before Parliament in the Queen’s Speech.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-07-12T15:02:46.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532888/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532888/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-05","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of which policy areas within his Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532889","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-11T14:24:18.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532889/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532889/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-05","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of which policy areas within his Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41965"
