"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532980","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-11","<p>The UK continues to press for sustained humanitarian access to all besieged and hard to reach areas in Syria. We are a core member of the International Syria Support Group (ISSG), which demanded in May that the Asad regime allow land access to all besieged areas from 1 June, or the international community would call on the World Food Programme (WFP) to carry out humanitarian airdrops to those areas. This was only necessary because the regime has consistently failed to live up to its commitments under International Humanitarian Law to ensure free, unimpeded access for humanitarian agencies.</p><p>As a result, June saw improved levels of humanitarian access. Eight besieged locations were reached by road, including Darayya which received its first deliveries of food since 2012. However, seven remained unreached at the end of June. The regime has now agreed in principle road access to all 16 besieged areas requested by the UN in July. The ISSG is working with the UN to hold the regime to this commitment.</p><p>While delivering aid by road is the best approach to safely deliver the quantities needed and to ensure that it gets to those who need it most, if there is no improvement we must look to the WFP to carry out its plan for airdrops to reach those in need. The ISSG is united in its resolve to ensure full, sustained humanitarian access to the people of Syria.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-07-11T16:30:45.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532980/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532980/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-05","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to commence aid drops in Syria.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","41931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532981","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-11","<p>We are aware of the El Nino induced drought affecting some regions of the Philippines. The Department for International Development have also provided funding to the UK Met Office to provide technical assistance to Philippine Atmospheric Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration (PAGASA).</p><p>The Philippines has a well-developed disaster management system that is appropriately resourced; we judge that the impact of El Nino does not exceed the Government of Philippines’s capacity to respond. Should the Philippines require external assistance, Association of Southeast Asian Nations should constitute the first line of international response.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-07-11T16:32:33.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532981/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532981/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-05","Philippines: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she has taken to assist people in the Filipino province of Davao del Norte affected by the recent drought.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","41868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532982","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-07-12T16:20:46.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532982/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532982/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-05","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of which policy areas within her Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532983","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-07-12T15:05:50.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532983/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532983/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of which policy areas within his Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532984","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-12","<p>The UK has a proud tradition of respect for human rights and will continue to protect fundamental human rights.</p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-07-12T15:00:50.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532984/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532984/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment the Government has made of the potential implications for UK human rights legislation of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532985","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-11","<p>All external adverts for posts at HMP Berwyn have been published in both English and Welsh language.</p><p>Posts did not stipulate Welsh language skills as a requirement, but we expect Welsh and English to be spoken by at least some staff in all functional areas.</p><p>Data on the number of bilingual Welsh and English speakers appointed is not collected centrally.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","41853","2016-07-11T16:58:20.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532985/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532985/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many posts have been advertised at HM Prison Berwyn for which Welsh language skills were stipulated as (a) essential and (b) desirable; and what proportion of (i) advertised posts and (ii) total posts such posts represented in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","41852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532986","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-11","<p>All external adverts for posts at HMP Berwyn have been published in both English and Welsh language.</p><p>Posts did not stipulate Welsh language skills as a requirement, but we expect Welsh and English to be spoken by at least some staff in all functional areas.</p><p>Data on the number of bilingual Welsh and English speakers appointed is not collected centrally.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","41852","2016-07-11T16:58:20.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532986/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532986/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of appointments to HM Prison Berwyn have been of bilingual Welsh and English speakers; and what proportion such staff are of the total employed at that prison.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","41853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532987","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-11","<p>The majority of decisions are overturned at appeal for two reasons: (i) the oral evidence given by claimants on the day of the hearing; (ii) new written evidence provided at the hearing.</p><p> </p><p>DWP, as part of its appeal reforms, introduced Mandatory Reconsideration – the pre-appeal dispute stage. This gives claimants the opportunity to have their decision reviewed and corrected much sooner than at appeal.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst this reform is working, DWP is reviewing its decision making processes both in relation to the initial decision and the Mandatory Reconsideration stage, to ensure that it does gather all relevant evidence ahead of any appeal hearing – and that this is reflected in the appeal response considered by the tribunal.</p><p> </p><p>The department is also introducing Presenting Officers to attend send to appeals for these benefits, thereby giving the Secretary of State the opportunity to consider the evidence being presented by the claimant at the hearing and feedback to the department.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-11T13:45:31.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532987/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532987/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-05","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in successful appeals against decisions on personal independence payment and employment and support allowance claims at tribunal stage.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","41874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532988","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-07-12T14:53:15.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532988/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532988/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to introduce legislative proposals to limit the effect of EU law and the role of the Court of Justice of the EU within the UK during the period of negotiation on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","41871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532989","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Government is absolutely clear that victims of domestic violence must have access to the help that they need, including access to legal aid.</p><p>We are working closely with various domestic abuse support groups and legal representative bodies to gather information about the existing evidence requirements for obtaining legal aid in private family law cases involving domestic violence.</p><p>Whilst examination of means testing is not the purpose of this exercise, the review may uncover any issues relating to application of the means test to this particular group.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-07-13T15:16:07.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532989/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532989/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-05","Legal Aid Scheme: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to investigate the effect of means testing for legal aid on the ability of domestic violence survivors to access justice.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","41872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532990","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The outgoing Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we now need to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-13T07:53:49.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532990/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532990/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-07-05","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of which policy areas within her Department's remit will be affected by the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","41975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532991","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-11","NATO Summits do not formally discuss Articles of the Washington Treaty as items of their formal agenda. However, the importance of strong institutions at national level was reflected in several of the themes and topics addressed at the Warsaw Summit on 8-9 July. For example, Allies reaffirmed their commitment to achieving the NATO defence investment targets agreed at the 2014 Wales Summit through national action plans; to improving NATO-EU cooperation in support of a comprehensive approach to security; and to building resilience in the face of hybrid threats, also requiring strong national institutions. NATO remains at the heart of UK defence and security policy and we are at the forefront of NATO’s efforts to modernise and adapt to today’s threat picture. We continue to work through NATO with our key allies across the globe to multiply the effects of our own determined approach, to project stability and increase our collective security, including in line the aims of with Article 2 of the Washington Treaty.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","41900","2016-07-11T16:22:06.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532991/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532991/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-05","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether Article 2 of the North Atlantic Treaty will be on the agenda of the forthcoming NATO summit.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","41870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532992","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-11","NATO Summits do not formally discuss Articles of the Washington Treaty as items of their formal agenda. However, the importance of strong institutions at national level was reflected in several of the themes and topics addressed at the Warsaw Summit on 8-9 July. For example, Allies reaffirmed their commitment to achieving the NATO defence investment targets agreed at the 2014 Wales Summit through national action plans; to improving NATO-EU cooperation in support of a comprehensive approach to security; and to building resilience in the face of hybrid threats, also requiring strong national institutions. NATO remains at the heart of UK defence and security policy and we are at the forefront of NATO’s efforts to modernise and adapt to today’s threat picture. We continue to work through NATO with our key allies across the globe to multiply the effects of our own determined approach, to project stability and increase our collective security, including in line the aims of with Article 2 of the Washington Treaty.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","41870","2016-07-11T16:22:06.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532992/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532992/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-05","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to fulfil Article 2 of the North Atlantic Treaty.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","41900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532993","Scotland Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>Competence for a referendum on Scottish independence rests with the UK Parliament. Less than two years ago the people of Scotland voted decisively to remain part of the United Kingdom. The Edinburgh Agreement committed both the UK and Scottish Governments to respect this result.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-07-12T11:46:05.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532993/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532993/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-07-05","Sovereignty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether an Act of Parliament would be required to allow a further binding referendum on Scottish independence.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","41892"
