"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532344","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The United Kingdom value the historic relationship of trust and cooperation that we share with the Republic of Mauritius. It is therefore with great concern that we note the intention the Prime Minister of Mauritius expressed to the Parliament of Mauritius on 17 May to seek a referral by the UN General Assembly to the International Court of Justice this autumn, in order to obtain an advisory opinion in relation to the British Indian Ocean Territory (Chagos Archipelago).</p><p>Referral of this matter to the International Court of Justice would cause lasting damage to Mauritius’ bilateral relations and we have respectfully sought the Prime Minister of Mauritius’ assurance that he does not intend to proceed with such action, and that he will return to a constructive path. Mauritius stands to benefit from friendly relations, including in relation to the British Indian Ocean Territory, where the UK and Mauritius are already engaged in talks that aim to implement the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea arbitral award of March 2015 and give due regard to Mauritius’ interests in matters of marine conservation in the British Indian Ocean Territory.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:17:25.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532344/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532344/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to maintain current relations with Mauritius, in the light of the intention of Mauritius to seek an advisory opinion from the International Court of Justice on the sovereignty of Mauritius over the Chagos Archipelago.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532345","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The United Kingdom will continue to consider, on a case-by-case basis, whether to support any properly formulated request for an advisory opinion from the International Court of Justice on legal questions from duly authorised bodies, in accordance with Article 96 of the UN Charter.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:16:43.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532345/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532345/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to make greater use of the advisory function of the International Court of Justice.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532346","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The United Kingdom is committed to cede the territory to Mauritius when it is no longer required for defence purposes. <br>The military facility located in the British Indian Ocean Territory continues to contribute significantly towards global security, and is central to efforts at countering regional threats, including those from terrorism and piracy. We do not envisage this position changing in the short-term and it is for the UK alone to determine when this position has been reached.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL944","2016-07-13T15:16:22.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532346/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532346/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Palestinians: Ambulance Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the timescale for ending the use of the Chagos Archipelago for defence purposes.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532347","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The United Kingdom is committed to cede the territory to Mauritius when it is no longer required for defence purposes. <br>The military facility located in the British Indian Ocean Territory continues to contribute significantly towards global security, and is central to efforts at countering regional threats, including those from terrorism and piracy. We do not envisage this position changing in the short-term and it is for the UK alone to determine when this position has been reached.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL943","2016-07-13T15:16:22.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532347/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532347/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","West Bank: EU Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how long after the ending of the use of the Chagos Archipelago for defence purposes they expect to return that territory to Mauritius.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532348","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-18","<p>There are 25 species of bumblebee resident in the UK, including the short-haired bumblebee which is currently being re-introduced under Natural England’s Species Recovery Programme.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014 Defra published independent research on the status of pollinators in the UK. The study identified an overall decline in wild bee diversity over the last 50 years. This concluded that bumblebee species that have become less widespread are associated with the loss of flower-rich habitat, driven by changes in agricultural land use and urbanisation.</p><p> </p><p>Both Environmental Stewardship and now the new Countryside Stewardship schemes fund the provision of food and habitat for wild pollinators. The new scheme in particular incorporates a Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife package which provides year-round food, winter shelter and nesting places essential for pollinators.</p><p> </p><p>Although honeybees face many of these environmental pressures their population is driven by the number of beekeepers willing and able to keep bees. There is some evidence that the number of beekeepers, and therefore the number of honey bees, may have increased since 2009 as more keepers are registered on the National Bee Unit’s BeeBase and with beekeeping associations.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL946","2016-07-18T16:55:43.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532348/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532348/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Crisis Care Concordat Steering Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many species of bumblebee there are in the UK, and what assessment they have made of the challenges faced by those species.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532349","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-18","<p>There are 25 species of bumblebee resident in the UK, including the short-haired bumblebee which is currently being re-introduced under Natural England’s Species Recovery Programme.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014 Defra published independent research on the status of pollinators in the UK. The study identified an overall decline in wild bee diversity over the last 50 years. This concluded that bumblebee species that have become less widespread are associated with the loss of flower-rich habitat, driven by changes in agricultural land use and urbanisation.</p><p> </p><p>Both Environmental Stewardship and now the new Countryside Stewardship schemes fund the provision of food and habitat for wild pollinators. The new scheme in particular incorporates a Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife package which provides year-round food, winter shelter and nesting places essential for pollinators.</p><p> </p><p>Although honeybees face many of these environmental pressures their population is driven by the number of beekeepers willing and able to keep bees. There is some evidence that the number of beekeepers, and therefore the number of honey bees, may have increased since 2009 as more keepers are registered on the National Bee Unit’s BeeBase and with beekeeping associations.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL945","2016-07-18T16:55:43.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532349/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532349/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Bath University: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the challenges facing honeybees in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Barones