li><li><strong>2013</strong>- 572 candidates were recommended out of which 38 (7%) were from BAME backgrounds, 303 (53%) were women and 81 (14%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2014</strong>- 312 candidates were recommended out of which 40 (13%) were from BAME backgrounds, 134 (43%) were women and 11 (4%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2015</strong>- 319 candidates were recommended out of which 28 (9%) were from BAME backgrounds, 143 (45%) were women and 10 (3%) were disabled.</li></ul><p>The Government acknowledges that within the judiciary there is an under-representation of women, those who are disabled and those from a BAME background. However, recent statistics show some improvement which suggests ongoing diversity initiatives, co-ordinated by the Forum, are beginning to have an impact:</p><p> </p><p>1) 12% of judges across Courts and Tribunals under 50 years of age are from a BAME background (around 14% of the UK population are from BAME groups).</p><p>2) JAC Official Statistics from April 2015 to March 2016 showed women made up 45% of those recommended for appointment overall (140 of 308 recommendations).</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL947 ; HL948 ; HL950","2016-07-18T13:55:32.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532352/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532352/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Bath University: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what resources they have provided for diversity and equality initiatives in the judiciary; and what assessment they have made of the success of those initiatives to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532353","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Government is committed to improving judicial diversity and co-ordinates this effort through the Judicial Diversity Forum, a cross-stakeholder group with representatives from the Ministry of Justice, Judicial Appointments Commission (JAC), the judiciary and legal profession.</p><p> </p><p>The Judicial Diversity Forum replaced the Judicial Diversity Taskforce in 2014 as the body responsible for encouraging judicial diversity; it has implemented a number of schemes to help improve judicial diversity. Recent examples include the 100 plus Diversity and Community Relations Judges doing invaluable work with the community to expel myths about working for the judiciary and interact with schools, universities and the legal professions. There is also a Judicial Mentoring Scheme where judges volunteer to be mentors; providing invaluable advice and guidance to those from under-represented groups seeking a judicial appointment or those wishing to progress in their judicial career.</p><p> </p><p>Data on judicial appointments are published regularly on gov.uk. The below figures show how many candidates were recommended by the JAC for judicial appointment in each of the past six years and how many of those were (1) from black and minority ethnic (BAME) backgrounds, (2) women and (3) disabled. As these figures are JAC recommendations, they may include a small number of candidates that do not go on to be appointed.</p><p> </p><ul><li><strong>2010</strong>- 759 candidates were recommended out of which 75 (10%) were from BAME, 309 (41%) were women and 41 (5%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2011</strong>- 894 candidates were recommended out of which 91 (10%) were from BAME backgrounds, 406 (45%) were women and 34 (4%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2012</strong>- 371 candidates were recommended out of which 48 (13%) were from BAME backgrounds, 152 (41%) were women and 22 (6%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2013</strong>- 572 candidates were recommended out of which 38 (7%) were from BAME backgrounds, 303 (53%) were women and 81 (14%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2014</strong>- 312 candidates were recommended out of which 40 (13%) were from BAME backgrounds, 134 (43%) were women and 11 (4%) were disabled.</li><li><strong>2015</strong>- 319 candidates were recommended out of which 28 (9%) were from BAME backgrounds, 143 (45%) were women and 10 (3%) were disabled.</li></ul><p>The Government acknowledges that within the judiciary there is an under-representation of women, those who are disabled and those from a BAME background. However, recent statistics show some improvement which suggests ongoing diversity initiatives, co-ordinated by the Forum, are beginning to have an impact:</p><p> </p><p>1) 12% of judges across Courts and Tribunals under 50 years of age are from a BAME background (around 14% of the UK population are from BAME groups).</p><p>2) JAC Official Statistics from April 2015 to March 2016 showed women made up 45% of those recommended for appointment overall (140 of 308 recommendations).</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL947 ; HL948 ; HL949","2016-07-18T13:55:32.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532353/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532353/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Higher Education: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to support the development and introduction of pre-appointment training for those from under-represented groups seeking judicial appointments.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532354","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>An initial study has been undertaken to explore how to maximise, as far as reasonably practicable, the movement of material by rail at Euston. The study highlights a number of technical options which are now being assessed in detail with respect to their impact on passengers, their environmental and socio-economic impacts, and impacts on the HS2 programme. An initial decision on how to proceed will be made following the completion of this further assessment which is expected to be in advance of the HS2 Select Committee in the House of Lords hearing petitions in relation to Euston.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-12T12:33:21.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532354/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532354/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Higher Education: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect High Speed Two (HS2) Ltd to have completed its report on the potential maximisation of rail use for the handling of spoil and construction materials.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532355","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Government recognises that congestion can affect the predictability and length of bus journey times and the reliability of buses. In 2015, the Department for Transport published its externally commissioned research into factors that influence bus journey times, which is attached for your ease of reference. This work included a literature review of the existing body of work in this area at the time the research was conducted.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of local bus services operate on the local road network for which local authorities, rather than the Secretary of State, are responsible. Local traffic authorities have a duty under section 16 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 to manage their road network so as to secure the expeditious movement of traffic, including bus services, on the network.</p><p> </p><p>The Bus Services Bill recognises the important role local transport authorities have in this regard, providing them with new means to work in partnership with bus operators to achieve improvements to local bus services that benefit passengers and local communities.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-13T14:18:47.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532355/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532355/answer","HL0952 - bjtv-pilot-sudy-and-analysis-report.pdf ; HL0952 - bjtv-technical-report.pdf","HL0952 - bjtv-pilot-sudy-and-analysis-report.pdf ; HL0952 - bjtv-technical-report.pdf","Bus Journey Time Variablility - Pilot Study Report ; Bus Journey Time Variability - Technical Report","Bus Journey Time Variablility - Pilot Study Report ; Bus Journey Time Variability - Technical Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532355/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports that increased congestion is affecting bus journey times and the reliability of bus services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532356","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government has no current plans to introduce primary legislation to modernise the regulation of taxis and private hire vehicles.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-12T10:58:20.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532356/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532356/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to introduce legislation to modernise the regulation of taxis and private hire vehicles.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532357","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>We are determined to deliver better journeys for drivers and cut congestion. Lane rental enables councils to charge utilities companies for carrying out works on the busiest roads at the busiest times, to encourage them to keep disruption to a minimum on the local road network.</p><p> </p><p>Regulations and guidance were introduced in 2012 and led to the introduction of pioneer schemes by Transport for London in 2012 and Kent County Council in 2013. Charges were also applied under these schemes to the highway authority’s own maintenance works. The Department for Transport published an independent evaluation of the schemes in March 2016, which is attached for ease.</p><p> </p><p>The report is being used by the Department alongside other information to formulate options for the future of lane rental schemes. These are likely to be subject to consultation during 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-13T14:16:42.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532357/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532357/answer","HL0954 - ecorys-lane-rental-report.pdf","HL0954 - ecorys-lane-rental-report.pdf","Street Works Lane Rental Evaluation Report","Street Works Lane Rental Evaluation Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532357/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to encourage the wider use of lane rental schemes, as introduced in London in 2012.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532358","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>Under the Bus Subsidy Operators Grant (BSOG) system, the Government pays out some £250m a year to bus operators and local authorities to support bus services outside London.</p><p> </p><p>BSOG plays an important role in protecting services, especially in rural areas. Department for Transport analysis indicates that BSOG has helped extend the rural bus network by 13%, equivalent to an additional 38 million kilometres to the network, providing residents with vital links to local services.</p><p> </p><p>Ultimately, however, it is for individual authorities to decide which services are most appropriate for support in their respective areas and deliver the greatest benefits for their residents. We believe it is right that such decisions should be made locally.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-13T14:15:17.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532358/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532358/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the various levels of subsidy available for travel on public transport and the effect such variations have on inequality; and whether they plan to modify their policies as a result of that assessment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532359","Department for Education","false","2016-07-13","<p>The care leaver covenant will allow public, private and charitable bodies to set out how, as members of civil society, they will make a commitment to support care leavers to thrive into adulthood.</p><p> </p><p>We plan to launch the care leaver covenant during ‘care leavers’ week’ in October 2016.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-13T16:14:07.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532359/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532359/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-04","Care Leavers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to publish their care leaver covenant.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532360","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>The following table shows the funding allocated to the Frontline social work trainee programme, the Think Ahead trainee programme, the Step Up to Social Work trainee programme and social work teaching partnerships in the 2016-17 financial year.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Programme</p></td><td><p>2016-17 £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Frontline social work trainee programme Contract to deliver a national fast-track programme Pilot grant</p></td><td><p>2.4 7.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Think Ahead trainee programme</p></td><td><p>4.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Step Up to Social Work trainee programme</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social work teaching partnerships</p></td><td><p>7.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The 2016-17 funding for university social work programmes via student bursaries and the Education Support Grant is currently being finalised and as such is not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>The final costs of the assessment and accreditation system for child and family social workers are subject to future procurement, but will be met within the Department for Education (DfE) Spending Review settlement.</p><p> </p><p>The budgets in future years for each of these programmes, with the exception of the contract with Frontline, an independent charitable organisation, to deliver a national fast-track programme, are not yet agreed and are subject to business planning in the normal way.</p><p> </p><p>DfE has a protected budget of £320 million each year of the Spending Review period for children’s services and Ministers are in the process of making decisions about how best to allocate resources within this envelope. DfE programme figures in this response show the allocations which have already been made.</p><p> </p><p>The following table below shows the allocations to Frontline, up to and including 2019-20, to deliver a national fast-track programme.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Programme</p></td><td><p>2017 – 18 £ million</p></td><td><p>2018 – 19 £ million</p></td><td><p>2019 – 20 £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Contract to deliver a national fast-track programme</p></td><td><p>11.07</p></td><td><p>16.24</p></td><td><p>18.49</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-12T13:55:18.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532360/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532360/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-04","School Libraries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what resources were allocated in, or are planned for, (1) 2016–17, (2) 2017–18, (3) 2018–19, and (4) 2019–20, for (a) university social work programmes via student bursaries and the Training Support Grant; (b) the Frontline social work trainee programme; (c) the Think Ahead trainee programme; (d) the Step Up to Social Work trainee programme; (e) social work teaching partnerships; and (f) the start-up and continuing costs for the accreditation of child and family social work.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532361","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-07-14","<p>All users, including Members, agree to abide by Parliament’s Acceptable Use Policy every time they log on to the Parliamentary Network. This policy makes clear that the Parliamentary Digital Service provides systems to protect Parliamentary users (and the network) from malicious attack.</p><p>The Messagelabs service is an important part of the infrastructure protecting Members and the wider Parliamentary Network against malicious attack. It is a fully automated scanning service which scans for and blocks emails that are potential vectors for cyber-attack. It also scans for and quarantines emails that are suspected spam, again using fully automated systems. It does not involve any other form of monitoring of the content of parliamentary email.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-07-14T12:43:34.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532361/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532361/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-07-04","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees whether any members of the House have been asked to provide written consent for their Parliamentary emails to be monitored by MessageLabs antivirus software.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532362","Department of Health","false","2016-07-11","<p>There is no discrepancy, merely an imbalance due to demographic factors. European Union healthcare rules ensure that millions of United Kingdom citizens who work, visit or retire to other European countries can receive the free or reduced cost healthcare they need. Some 80% of the UK’s European Economic Area healthcare bill is for our pensioners who chose to retire to Europe.</p><p> </p><p>As many more of our pensioners choose to retire to other EEA countries than pensioners from those countries retiring to the UK, it is inevitable we will pay more to cover the healthcare costs of people insured by the UK than we will receive from other EEA countries. People from Europe who choose to live, work and pay tax in the UK are fully covered by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>All EEA counties, including the UK, have a legal obligation to pay agreed claims relating to healthcare treatment provided. Once both sides are satisfied that such claims are accurate, they are paid in full.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-11T12:30:20.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532362/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532362/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-04","Public Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 13 June (HL566), what assessment they have made of the discrepancy between the total claims made by the UK against EEA countries and Switzerland and the total claims made against the UK by EEA countries and Switzerland.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532363","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>On 5 July, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood), issued a Statement expressing deep concern about the announcement of new settlements units in the West Bank, including East Jerusalem.</p><p>Whilst officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv have not yet raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, Mr Ellwood said in his statement &quot;Settlements are illegal under international law. As noted in the report issued by the Middle East Quartet on 1 July, steps like this also make a two state solution more difficult to achieve.&quot;</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:13:39.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532363/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532363/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","General Practitioners: Opening Hours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they intend to take in response to the government of Israel's recent announcements of additional settlements on the West Bank and what representations they have made to that government about the impact of those announcements on the viability of a two-state solution.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532364","Department for Education","false","2016-07-25","<p>As this is a devolved matter, we can only answer regarding the institutions that received degree awarding powers in England. These figures are based on the information available to us.</p><p> </p><p>(1a) Between 1986 and 2000 in England, 48 institutions were awarded degree awarding powers. At this time there was no distinction between taught and research degree awarding powers, and foundation degree awarding powers were not yet introduced.</p><p>(1b) Between 2001 and 2015 in England, 42 institutions were awarded taught degree awarding powers and 4 institutions were awarded foundation degree awarding powers. 8 institutions also added research degree awarding powers to their pre-existing awards of taught degree awarding powers. 46 institutions in total were awarded degree awarding powers.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-25T12:30:31.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532364/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532364/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-04","Financial Services: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many institutions received degree-awarding powers in (1) England, and (2) the UK, between (a) 1986 and 2000, and (b) 2001 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532365","Department for Education","false","2016-07-25","<p>As this is a devolved matter, we can only answer regarding the institutions that received degree awarding powers in England. These figures are based on the information available to us.</p><p> </p><p>(1a) Between 1986 and 2000 in England, 33 institutions were awarded University Title. All of these were awarded to former polytechnics as a result of the Further and Higher Education Act 1992.</p><p>(1b) Between 2001 and 2015 in England, 36 institutions were awarded University Title.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-25T12:29:56.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532365/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532365/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-04","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many institutions received the title of university in (1) England, and (2) the UK, between (a) 1986 and 2000, and (b) 2001 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532366","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-18","<p>On 9 November 2015, the government announced a £1.3bn investment to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation. As part of this programme the Ministry of Justice will build new prison places while selling ageing, inefficient prisons to free up land for new homes.These new prisons will be designed to enable prisoners to engage with the educational and other rehabilitative services they need in order to turn their lives around and re-join their communities.</p><p> </p><p>We are in the process of finding sites for new prisons, looking at our own and other government departments’ land holdings, contacting Local Authorities and considering other available sites. No decisions have yet been made on the locations of the new prisons. At the time we indicate our intention to proceed with a site we will carry out a public engagement event in the local area, working with the local authority and others to progress the site through the planning permission process.</p><p> </p><p>Following a decision to close a prison and it subsequently being decommissioned the Ministry of Justice will prepare the site for disposal. The Ministry of Justice will work closely with the local authority and others, on future options for the site. Once a decision is made, the MoJ and its advisors will engage with the market and other stakeholders. No decisions have yet been made about prison sales.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-07-18T13:53:15.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532366/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532366/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the consultation process for the prison sale and building programme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532367","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-18","<p>The anticipated value of contracts for Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRC) was published in the Official Journal of the European Union on 4 February 2015.</p><p>CRCs are currently undergoing transformation including changes to their workforce. The proportion of cost spent on direct front line staff in the final operating model for each CRC will be different to the proportion of cost at the point of contract award and which will continue to vary from month to month until transformation is complete.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-07-18T13:53:45.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532367/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532367/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the contract value allocated to each Community Rehabilitation Company and what percentage is spent on direct front line delivery staff as opposed to contract management staff.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532368","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-13","<p>On 9 November 2015, the government announced a £1.3bn investment to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Justice announced on 25 November 2015 that HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Holloway would be closed as the first stage of this programme. HMP Holloway was closed on 22 June. Once the prison has been fully decommissioned it will be handed over to the Ministry of Justice Estates Directorate for disposal.</p><p> </p><p>No decisions have yet been taken on the future of the Holloway site. The Ministry of Justice will work closely with the local authority and others, on future options for the site. Once a decision is made, the MoJ and its advisors will engage with the market and other stakeholders. Any valuation information is considered commercially sensitive and therefore cannot be released.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL966 ; HL967","2016-07-13T15:00:29.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532368/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532368/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the most up to date commercial land market valuation for the Holloway Prison site.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532369","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-13","<p>On 9 November 2015, the government announced a £1.3bn investment to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Justice announced on 25 November 2015 that HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Holloway would be closed as the first stage of this programme. HMP Holloway was closed on 22 June. Once the prison has been fully decommissioned it will be handed over to the Ministry of Justice Estates Directorate for disposal.</p><p> </p><p>No decisions have yet been taken on the future of the Holloway site. The Ministry of Justice will work closely with the local authority and others, on future options for the site. Once a decision is made, the MoJ and its advisors will engage with the market and other stakeholders. Any valuation information is considered commercially sensitive and therefore cannot be released.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL965 ; HL967","2016-07-13T15:00:29.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532369/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532369/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is decisions have been made about the future of the Holloway Prison site.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532370","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-13","<p>On 9 November 2015, the government announced a £1.3bn investment to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Justice announced on 25 November 2015 that HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Holloway would be closed as the first stage of this programme. HMP Holloway was closed on 22 June. Once the prison has been fully decommissioned it will be handed over to the Ministry of Justice Estates Directorate for disposal.</p><p> </p><p>No decisions have yet been taken on the future of the Holloway site. The Ministry of Justice will work closely with the local authority and others, on future options for the site. Once a decision is made, the MoJ and its advisors will engage with the market and other stakeholders. Any valuation information is considered commercially sensitive and therefore cannot be released.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL965 ; HL966","2016-07-13T15:00:29.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532370/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532370/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for the marketing of the Holloway Prison site.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532371","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-13","<p>All women transferred from Holloway were carefully assessed as part of the prison’s closure planning. The assessment sought to ensure that they were held as close to home as was practicable given their individual circumstances.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-07-13T15:03:48.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532371/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532371/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-04","Patients: Transport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to monitor the impact of the closure of Holloway Prison on the number of family visits to relocated prisoners.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532372","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-15","<p>International law does not require states to regulate the extraterritorial activities of their businesses. Individual states are responsible for protecting against and prosecuting human rights and other abuses that are committed within their borders. The United Kingdom is one of few jurisdictions globally where victims of human rights abuses allegedly committed overseas by a British domiciled company can bring a civil case to the UK courts.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-15T13:43:17.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532372/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532372/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Health Professions: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 27 June (HL744), what steps they plan to take if they find British businesses not complying with the UK National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights in countries like Colombia.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532373","Home Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>We are concerned by the increase in reported hate crime in recent days. We are working alongside communities and police to and monitor the situation and encourage people who may be subject to racist or religious abuse of any kind to report it to the police.</p><p>This Government is committed to tackling hate crime. The UK has one of the strongest legislative frameworks in the world to tackle hate crime. We are working across Government with police, (including National Community Tensions Team), the Crown Prosecution Service and community partners to send out a clear message that hate crime will not be tolerated and we will vigorously pursue and prosecute those who commit these crimes.</p><p>We will shortly be publishing a new Hate Crime Action Plan, covering all forms of hate crime, including xenophobic attacks. The plan has been developed in partnership with communities and departments across Government.</p><p>We want to ensure victims of hate crime are supported and in December 2013, we brought into force a new Code of Practice for Victims of Crime which includes an enhanced level of service for victims of the most serious crime, including victims of hate crime.</p><p>We will continue to work across Government, the criminal justice system and with community partners to provide support for victims and put a stop to hate crime in all its forms.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-12T13:27:49.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532373/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532373/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of report by the National Police Chiefs' Council suggesting a 57 per cent increase in hate crimes in the UK since the referendum on UK membership of the EU, what steps they intend to take to tackle intolerance and racially motivated crime.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532374","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-18","<p>In 2015, the membership of the Tourism Industry Council was refreshed and the meeting format revised, so that the Council's discussions inform those of the newly established inter-Ministerial group on Tourism. The last meeting of the Inter-Ministerial Group took place in February.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-07-18T15:05:27.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532374/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532374/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Fares","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Inter-Ministerial Group last met, and what conclusions were made about establishing the Tourism Industry Council.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532375","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Five Point Plan on Tourism encourages visitors to travel beyond the capital. In 2015, the South East, South West, West Midlands and the North East of England saw both international visits and spend growing at a faster rate than in London. The £40m Discover England Fund aims to further encourage international visitors to explore right across the country and the first tranche of successful bids will be announced shortly.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-07-18T15:17:28.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532375/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532375/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Camden","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made to ensure that the aim to distribute inbound tourism across the UK, as set out in the Five Point Plan, will be met.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532376","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-18","<p>In the last five years 277 new fit-for-purpose pools have been built in locations which best serve the needs of people in the local community. The number of swimming pools and amount of pool space has increased since 2007.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England is supporting over 80 local authorities to develop a strategic approach to facility provision, making sure that community facilities like swimming pools are in the right location and are sustainable</p><p> </p><p>As Sport England moves towards the implementation of its new strategy, 'Towards an Active Nation', it will be working with partners across the swimming industry to explore how to get more people swimming.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-07-18T15:18:26.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532376/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532376/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the findings of the 2016 <i>UK Swimming Industry Report</i> that the number of swimming sites is in decline, what steps they intend to take to reduce that decline.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532377","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>There will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of European nationals who wish to travel, study and work in the UK.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T13:04:10.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532377/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-04","Cycleways","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact that the result of the referendum on UK membership of the EU will have on the free movement of football players from EU member states and their ability to continue to play football in UK football clubs.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532378","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>United Kingdom law relating to the rights of EU nationals and their family members to enter and reside in the UK is fully compliant with the decision of the Court of Justice of the European Union in C-127/08.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-14T13:04:30.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532378/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-04","Holiday Accommodation: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to bring UK law into line with the European Court of Justice ruling C-127/08 on the implementation of Directive 2004/38/EC and the rights of non-EU spouses of EU citizens to move freely in the EU.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532379","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin III Regulation is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-21T13:41:24.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532379/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532379/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-04","Holiday Accommodation: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many unaccompanied minors seeking asylum have been successfully transferred to the UK in each month since the introduction of Dublin III in January 2013, and from which countries those transfers were made.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532380","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","The Rainbow flag was previously flown at some United Kingdom Diplomatic missions. Since 2015, following the implementation of a simple, clear and consistent flag flying policy, United Kingdom Diplomatic missions have only flown the Diplomatic, Union or Consular flag, the flags of the constituent countries of the UK on their respective national days and in certain countries, the European flag. United Kingdom Diplomatic missions do not fly any other flags.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:14:12.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532380/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532380/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Holiday Accommodation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 4 July (HL763), why the pride flag was not flown over the British Embassy in Ankara when the pride flag has been flown over embassies in Paris, Oslo, Tel Aviv and Santiago.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532381","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>I refer the noble Lord to my answer of 4 July 2016 in response to his question of 20 June 2016 (HL763). This stated that we regularly underline the importance of all fundamental freedoms as part of our broader dialogue with the Turkish government, including freedom of assembly. We have expressed concerns over the disproportionate use of rubber bullets and tear gas by Turkish authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:14:30.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532381/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532381/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Police Federation Independent Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 4 July (HL763), why they have not discussed with the government of Turkey the use of rubber bullets and tear gas against LGBT people on the streets of Istanbul.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532382","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>I refer the noble Lord to my answer of 4 July in response to his question of 20 June 2016 (HL763), in which I stated that we regularly underline the importance of all fundamental freedoms as part of our broader dialogue with the Turkish government, including freedom of assembly. We have expressed concerns over the disproportionate use of rubber bullets and tear gas by Turkish authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-13T15:14:47.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532382/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532382/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-04","Paediatrics: Audiology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 4 July (HL763), when they plan to raise with the government of Turkey the use of tear gas and rubber bullets against LGBT people on the streets of Istanbul.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532385","Attorney General","false","2016-07-11","<p>No such payments have been made by any of the Law Officers’ Departments during the period 1 April 2011 to date.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-07-11T12:36:28.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532385/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532385/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-07-04","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much has been paid to officials of the Law Officers' Departments as an additional incentive for working overtime on top of their normal overtime payments in (a) each of the last five years and (b) 2016 to date; how much has been offered to any individual staff member for a one-off occurrence; how many staff received such incentivised additional payments; from which budgets such payments were made; and at which Ministerial or official level the business cases or payment approval for such payments was made.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","41800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532386","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has not paid officials an incentive for working overtime on top of their normal overtime payments over the last five years.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-07T10:23:21.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532386/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532386/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, (a) how much has been paid to officials of his Department as an additional incentive for working overtime on top of their normal overtime payments, (b) how much has been offered to any individual staff member for a one-off occurrence, (c) how many staff received such incentivised additional payments, (d) from which budgets such payments were made and (e) at which Ministerial or official level the business cases or payment approval for such payments was made in (i) each of the last five years and (ii) 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","41799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532387","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-08-26","<p>We are committed to working closely with the UK steel sector through the Steel Council, which is co-chaired by my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and the Chair of UK Steel, to maximize all opportunities to improve the sector’s competitiveness. This is also the forum for the Government and the Steel sector to work together to assess the implications of the outcome of the EU referendum. On 28 June, Ministers from the former Department of Business, Innovation and Skills held a special round table of business leaders, including the Chair of the Steel Council, to start to explore post-referendum issues.</p><p> </p><p>On 20 July, my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and I visited Port Talbot when we met with local Tata Steel management, employees and trade unions.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s top priority for steel has not changed in the light of the EU referendum. The process for selling Tata Steel’s remaining UK assets remains ongoing and we continue to work closely with Tata and potential bidders to seek to secure a sustainable future for UK steel production.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-08-26T12:04:35.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532387/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532387/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532387/answer/previousversion/6230","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with representatives of the UK steel industry on the implications of the outcome of the EU referendum for that industry; and what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies on support for the steel industry of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","41714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532388","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government is continuing to develop the Catapult network and has prioritised core funding support for the Catapult network in the 2015 Spending Review.</p><p>Northern Ireland (NI) is already benefitting from the Catapult Programme. The Digital Catapult has established local centres in Northern Ireland. It has just appointed a lead for its NI centres and is expecting the projects and activity to take shape and start in the coming months. The Precision Medicine Catapult will also be supported by a Centre of Excellence in Belfast.</p><p>A number of other Catapults also have strong links with business and academia in Northern Ireland. The Cell and Gene Therapy Catapult worked with a team at Queens University Belfast to define the path to commercialisation for a therapy to help treat retinal vein occlusion, a common cause of visual impairment and blindness affecting around 16.4 million people across the US, Europe, Asia and Australia.</p><p>The Northern Ireland Advanced Composites and Engineering Centre (NIACE) is a partner in the composites network with the National Composites Centre (NCC) of the High Value Manufacturing Catapult.</p><p>The High Value Manufacturing Catapult is also working with four industrial partners, including Bombardier Aerospace in Northern Ireland, on the VIEWS (Validation and Integration of Manufacturing Enablers for Future Wing Structures) Programme to bring promising wing design, manufacture and assembly technologies near to market readiness.</p><p>The Future Cities Catapult has been working closely with the City of Belfast to harness new technologies and help to fulfil their smart city ambitions and provide better services to its citizens by inviting SMEs to meet the challenge of increasing revenue from business rates across the city.</p><p>The Satellite Applications Catapult has a Knowledge Exchange Fellow based in Northern Ireland. This Fellowship, alongside funding from Invest Northern Ireland, is assisting an agricultural solutions business based in Northern Ireland to enhance its services through the utilisation of GNSS (Global Navigation Satellite System) technology.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-12T09:54:36.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532388/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532388/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Technology and Innovation Centres: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure Northern Ireland benefits from the Catapult programme.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","41766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532389","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills does not hold this data.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-11T14:12:44.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532389/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532389/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532389/answer/previousversion/6231","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","New Businesses: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many women started businesses in (a) Liverpool, Wavertree constituency, (b) the Liverpool City Region and (c) England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","41774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532390","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We are working to ensure we have the right business support for everyone, including women, to set up and grow a business. Start-Up Loans provide funding and intensive support to new entrepreneurs (39% of Start‑Up Loans have been awarded to women).</p><p> </p><p>There are 39 Growth Hubs across England and the Government has provided funding to Liverpool City Region to support development of a business growth hub that provides support to help businesses start-up and grow. The Business Support Helpline also provides information and guidance to people across England - 45% of users in the last year (April 2015-16) were women. In 2015 the Global Entrepreneurship Development Institute ranked the UK as the best country in Europe for female entrepreneurs.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T15:11:00.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532390/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532390/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what support his Department provides to female entrepreneurs in (a) Liverpool, Wavertree constituency, (b) the Liverpool City Region and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","41776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532391","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>While the UK is still a member of the EU, all rights and obligations will apply. We continue to support the EU’s trade agenda and the UK will participate constructively in EU decision making on trade issues. We are taking stock of our position with regard to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership and other trade negotiations.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T14:48:02.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532391/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532391/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership and other international trade negotiations.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532392","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>As my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has said, the negotiation with the European Union will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, who will take the decision about when to trigger article 50 and start the formal and legal process of leaving the European Union. Ministers will work closely with the new Prime Minister to set out the priorities for these negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-07T15:01:34.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532392/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532392/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has to negotiate access to the Digital Single Market for British online retailers.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532393","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has not made such an assessment. As my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has said, the negotiation with the European Union will begin under a new Prime Minister, who will take the decision about when to trigger article 50 and start the formal and legal process of leaving the European Union. We will work closely with the new Prime Minister to set out the priorities for these negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-07T14:59:48.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532393/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532393/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the cost to the economy of the (a) UK and (b) North East of the UK leaving the EU and businesses being unable to access the Digital Single Market.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532394","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>Consumer rights for the purchase of digital content are not regulated at EU level at present. In the UK the Consumer Rights Act 2015 provides UK consumers with bespoke consumer rights when buying digital content.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-07T15:19:34.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532394/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532394/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that digital consumer rights are not lost in the process of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532395","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-08-30","<p>On 28 June my Rt hon Friend the then Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills (Sajid Javid) chaired a Business Roundtable with representatives from the UK’s largest sectors that included manufacturing representatives who also cover those based in the North East.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-08-30T06:34:50.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532395/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532395/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532395/answer/previousversion/6232","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Manufacturing Industries: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what meetings he has had with manufacturers in the North East on the (a) immediate effect of the result of the EU referendum and (b) short to long-term effects of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532396","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p>The employment rate for the country as a whole is at a record high. Government is committed to ensuring that UK remains open for business, and continues to grow and thrive. The North East continues to have a positive balance of trade, with links to the global market as well as into the European Union. Government will continue to work with the North East Local Enterprise Partnership to deliver its Strategic Economic Plan, ‘More and Better Jobs’, which aims to build prosperity in the North East by increasing the skills base and creating more businesses.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T15:13:42.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532396/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532396/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Employment: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to protect employment levels in the North East from the potential (a) immediate effect of the UK voting to leave the UK and (b) the short to long-term effect of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532397","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-11","<p>In December 2015, the NAO issued the report ‘Companies in government’. As shown in Figure 7 of this report, at 31 March 2014 the government held special shares in 11 companies, across 5 departments. Changes since 31 March 2014 are shown in Figure 9 of the same report.</p><p> </p><p>The exact terms of those special shares will be a matter for the relevant Secretary of State, depending on the specific arrangements that were put in place for each company.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-11T11:25:08.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532397/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532397/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-04","Government Shareholding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which companies the Government retains golden shares in for the purpose of limiting overseas ownership; and what the terms are of such shares.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","41666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532398","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-09-08","<p>I have done so.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-08T09:35:30.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532398/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532398/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532398/answer/previousversion/6205","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects to answer Question 39267, tabled by the hon. Member for Brighton, Pavilion on 3 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","41740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532399","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-07","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office has established a new unit to deliver the outcome of the referendum, exploring options for our future relationship with Europe.</p><p> </p><p>As my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has said, it will be important to ensure that the interests of all parts of the United Kingdom are protected and advanced in our negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-07T15:08:42.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532399/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532399/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-04","Trade Agreements: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether officials from the Welsh Government have been identified to take part in the establishment of expanded trade negotiation functions in his Department as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","41710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532400","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The report of the Chilcot Inquiry was published on 6 July and is available to access online in searchable format. The Government takes very seriously its responsibility to all military veterans, especially those who have been injured in conflict, and a range of support mechanisms are available to Iraq veterans where required, including support in the transition to civilian life and access to pension and compensation schemes where injured as a result of their service. We will, of course, engage with and support any individuals who are concerned by any findings of Sir John Chilcot’s report.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:35:35.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532400/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532400/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532400/answer/previousversion/6179","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what support the Government plans to provide to veterans of the Iraq Conflict who are concerned by the findings of the Chilcot Report and its implications for their service records.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","41744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532401","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>Since the publication of the National Audit Office report earlier this year Cabinet Office has established updated governance on the Civil Service Pension Scheme, with a greater focus on service performance. This has helped facilitate an improvement in service performance from the pension administrator MyCSP. The Cabinet Office is committed to continuing to work with MyCSP to see this performance increase further still.</p><p>Through a process to re-set the contract with MyCSP the Cabinet Office is re-establishing the full service expectations and requirements under the contract. The focus going forward will be to work closely with MyCSP to ensure that all aspects of the service members receive is improving and is satisfactory to the scheme membership.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-12T08:23:41.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532401/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532401/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government has taken to improve the performance of the Civil Service Pension Scheme since the publication of the National Audit Office report, Investigation into Members' experience of civil service pension administration, published in February 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532402","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>Retired Civil Servants are not entitled to receive Annual Benefit Statements.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:20:05.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532402/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532402/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many retired civil servants have (a) not received an annual benefit statement and (b) received such a statement late from MyCSP in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532403","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>Where MyCSP has been notified by the member, or their employer, that they wish to receive their pension, all retired civil servants have had their pensions put into payment since MyCSP began processing such payments. Any pension entitlement not put into payment will be because either MyCSP has not been informed or because further information is required to enable the pension to be calculated accurately.</p><p>Of the Scheme’s 658,000 retired civil servants at transfer (14,000 of which were overseas pensioners), the vast majority continued to be paid accurately and on-time. Delays occurred for 36 overseas pensioners as new banking mandates had to be completed to allow processing by the new paying bank. It was subsequently discovered that the previous paying authority had not issued notification to any overseas pensioners advising them of the change in paying administration. All delayed cases were rectified promptly when the mandates were received.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-12T08:33:25.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532403/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532403/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many retired civil servants have not received pension payments from MyCSP for which they are eligible in (a) each of the last 12 months and (b) each month since MyCSP has been processing such payments.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532404","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The report of the Chilcot Inquiry was published on 6 July and is available to access online in searchable format. The Government takes very seriously its responsibility to all military veterans, especially those who have been injured in conflict, and a range of support mechanisms are available to Iraq veterans where required, including support in the transition to civilian life and access to pension and compensation schemes where injured as a result of their service. We will, of course, engage with and support any individuals who are concerned by any findings of Sir John Chilcot’s report.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:35:00.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532404/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532404/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532404/answer/previousversion/6176","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department has taken to provide similar support for injured veterans of the Iraq conflict following the publication of the Chilcot Report to that provided to the next of kin of people who lost their lives in that conflict.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","41752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532405","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>The report of the Chilcot Inquiry was published on 6 July and is available to access online in searchable format. The Government takes very seriously its responsibility to all military veterans, especially those who have been injured in conflict, and a range of support mechanisms are available to Iraq veterans where required, including support in the transition to civilian life and access to pension and compensation schemes where injured as a result of their service. We will, of course, engage with and support any individuals who are concerned by any findings of Sir John Chilcot’s report.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:35:18.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532405/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532405/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532405/answer/previousversion/6177","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2016 to Question 38697, what steps his Department has taken to provide injured veterans of the Iraq conflict with free copies of the Chilcot Report.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","41753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532406","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>In order to process payments in a timely manner, MyCSP is dependent on retirement requests being received from members (for deferred members) and Employers (for active members). Statistics are only kept on how MyCSP performs against the agreed Service Levels and this is what the responses below reflect. It should also be noted that the NAO report on customer experience made it clear that not all delays were the responsibility of MyCSP:</p><p>There are a number of stakeholders involved in the delivery of the administration of the civil service pensions. MyCSP depends on the participating employers and, where applicable, their shared service providers, for the provision of complete and accurate membership data on a timely basis. Where this is not provided, delays in providing quotations or making awards will occur which are not of MyCSP's making but members may perceive MyCSP as being at fault.</p><p>Since 01 July 2015, of 26,000 retirement awards processed, only 1 missed target, in August 2015:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Retirement awards processed</p></td><td><p>Processed within target</p></td><td><p>Missed target</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2015</p></td><td><p>692</p></td><td><p>692</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>2102</p></td><td><p>2101</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>3630</p></td><td><p>3630</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>2329</p></td><td><p>2329</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>1900</p></td><td><p>1900</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>1961</p></td><td><p>1961</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2016</p></td><td><p>1705</p></td><td><p>1705</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>1959</p></td><td><p>1959</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>2738</p></td><td><p>2738</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>2498</p></td><td><p>2498</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>2133</p></td><td><p>2133</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>2353</p></td><td><p>2353</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-12T08:20:13.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532406/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532406/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many retired civil servants have received late pension payments from MyCSP in (a) each of the last 12 months and (b) each month since that company has been processing such pension payments.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532407","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-11","<p>There are no cases currently marked as urgent awaiting processing by MyCSP.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-11T08:17:54.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532407/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532407/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many cases marked as urgent are currently waiting resolution by MyCSP.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532408","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>As highlighted in the NAO report published this year, it is estimated that 77% of current civil servant records have some level of data inconsistency or inaccuracy. However the majority of these do not have an impact on the calculation of pension benefits. 6.5% of member records data inaccuracies that mean pension benefits are misstated on the members annual benefit statement.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-13T07:38:33.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532408/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532408/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-04","Civil Servants: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants have pension records that are incomplete or incorrect.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","41659"
