"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532572","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Department recognises that everyone who uses the highway has a responsibility to behave safely and with consideration for others. If a person rides a cycle on a road without due care and attention, or without reasonable consideration for other persons using the road, he is guilty of the offence of careless cycling as set out in Section 29 of the Road Traffic Act 1988.</p><p> </p><p>We promote increased awareness of other road users and pedestrians through our Bikeability programme which has £50m funding to cover cycle training from 2016 - 2020. Bikeability not only provides trainees with riding skills suited to the road, but also explains the importance of obeying the Highway Code, the correct use of safety equipment, and sharing the road with other people.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-07T06:10:44.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532572/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532572/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-04","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to promote increased awareness among cyclists of other road users and pedestrians; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","41731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532574","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>This Government is committed to tackling disadvantage and extending opportunity so that everyone has the chance to realise their full potential. Our life chances approach will focus on tackling the root causes of poverty such as worklessness, educational attainment and family stability.</p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions recently published the 2014/15 Households Below Average Income (HBAI) statistics on 28<sup>th</sup> June 2016 alongside supporting data tables. Table 4.6db provides a regional breakdown of children in relative low income households, before and after housing costs. The latest estimates are shown as a three-year average over 2012/13-2014/15. These are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201415" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201415</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-07T16:21:20.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532574/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532574/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to publish child poverty statistics at a regional level.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","41727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532575","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government is committed to eliminating child poverty and improving life chances for children. We know that work is the best route out of poverty, and Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work. Evidence shows claimants move into work significantly faster and earn more than under the current system. In addition, Universal Credit now provides for 85% of childcare costs meaning more support for hardworking families.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-07T13:04:59.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532575/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532575/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of universal credit on the number of children living in (a) absolute and (b) relative poverty.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","41742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532576","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-11","<p>DWP’s use of the Dynamic Purchasing System in the North West has so far been restricted to Low Value Provision (LVP) of short vocational and occupational training to claimants who have a job offer or need training to be able to compete for vacancies in their local labour market.</p><p>DWP only records nationally the number of LVPs commissioned.</p><p>The recorded spend in 2014/15 in the North West was £577,737, of which £67,771 was spent in Merseyside and £2,375 by St Helens Jobcentre.</p><p>The recorded spend in 2015/16 in the North West was £670,526, of which £148,163 was spent in Merseyside and £15,698 by St Helens Jobcentre.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-11T16:18:34.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532576/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532576/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) value of programmes commissioned by his Department's Dynamic Purchasing System in (i) St Helens North constituency, (ii) Merseyside and (iii) the North West since that system was introduced.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","41706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532577","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Department has no plans to update these statistics.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-07T12:54:19.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532577/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532577/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish updated mortality statistics for employment and support allowance, incapacity benefit and severe disablement allowance.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","41684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532578","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention”, published 5 July 2016, reiterates that the Government will consider giving more responsibility to councils in England to support older people with care needs – including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance. Any new policy would protect existing claimants, and any new responsibilities would be matched by the transfer of equivalent spending power.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” closes at 12.00am on 26 September 2016, and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention</a></p><p>This is an open consultation and all interested parties are invited to respond. The Government would consult further in good time if changes are proposed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-07T15:55:06.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532578/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532578/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the timetable is for the consultation on attendance allowance.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","41665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532579","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not pay officials additional incentives for working overtime on top of their normal overtime payments.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-12T10:38:22.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532579/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532579/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, (a) how much has been paid to officials of his Department as an additional incentive for working overtime on top of their normal overtime payments, (b) how much has been offered to any individual staff member for a one-off occurrence, (c) how many staff received such incentivised additional payments, (d) from which budgets such payments were made and (e) at which Ministerial or official level the business cases or payment approval for such payments was made in (i) each of the last five years and (ii) 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","41816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532580","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>122 people from Hove (the BN3 postcode) made travel expense claims for attending assessments at Brighton Assessment Centre between 1 January and 19 November 2015.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-07-07T14:33:47.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532580/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532580/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Employment and Support Allowance: Hove","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment and support allowance claimants living in Hove constituency were reimbursed for travel to Brighton Assessment Centre in 2015.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","41783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532581","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>We do not hold the information you have requested, and this could only be collected and provided at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-07T14:14:02.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532581/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532581/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of personal independence payment claims which a tribunal ruled should be paid are reinstated within six to eight weeks.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532582","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>We do not hold the information requested about the average time taken, and this could only be collected and provided at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>In response to an Appeal decision the administrative stages for Personal Independence Payment are aligned with other benefits, and are summarised below:</p><p> </p><p>Following the appeal ruling, and receipt of the case papers back into the Department, an appeals case manager reviews the case and the appeal decision.</p><p> </p><p>Where the decision is accepted the appeal case manager will then progress to put the case into payment, including any arrears. This involves contacting the claimant to gather payment details if they are not held; and checking for any changes in circumstances that may affect the award amount - for example admission to hospital if the claimant is not currently receiving any payments.</p><p> </p><p>Where the decision is not accepted (that is, an appeals case manager identifies there has been a potential error in law) they will request a Statement of Reasons from the Tribunal Chairman. This must be requested by the Department within one month of receiving the appeal decision. Once the Statement of Reasons is received it is reviewed by the appeals case manager together with the case papers, who considers if a challenge to an Upper Tier Tribunal is appropriate. This must happen within one month of receiving the Statement of Reasons.</p><p> </p><p>There is no specific internal timeframe but we aim to deal with outcome decisions from PIP Appeals as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-07T14:26:23.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532582/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532582/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time taken is for a personal independence payment claim to resume after the claimant has successfully challenged a stop to their claim; what administrative stages his Department undertakes before resuming such payments; and what steps he is taking to ensure that the time taken to resume such payments is within service standards.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532583","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-07","<p>As Attendance Allowance awards are based on the need for care or supervision and not on mobility they do not give entitlement to the Motability scheme. This is also the case for the daily living component of PIP and the care component of DLA.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-07T14:48:10.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532583/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/532583/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-04","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether people claiming attendance allowance can access Motability.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533372","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>We have introduced a new system of extended tax averaging, allowing farmers to choose whether to spread their tax over a two or five-year period.</p><p>We are working on opening up new export markets for lamb. The Secretary of State had discussions on opening access for British lamb to the American market on her recent US trip.</p><p> </p><p>We are supporting the sector’s efforts to improve its efficiency and competitiveness through co-funded Agri-Tech projects.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-07T16:16:22.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533372/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533372/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Hill Farming: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent support her Department has given to lamb farmers.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","905717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533426","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Commission is currently collecting information to inform its statutory report on the Scottish Parliament elections. The report will include information about turnout and participation among 16- and 17-year-olds.</p><p>The report will also identify any conclusions which can be drawn from comparison with turnout and participation at previous polls, particularly the 2014 referendum.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2016-07-07T10:48:33.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533426/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533426/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2016-07-04","Scottish Parliament: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, if the Electoral Commission will make an assessment of the effect of extending the franchise for Scottish Parliament elections to 16 and 17 year olds on the level of youth engagement in the electoral process.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","905700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533487","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government’s ambition is to connect more children with nature. We have supported a number of initiatives for children to access and better understand the environment. Our aim is to not only give all children the chance to experience the natural world, but also to understand it, and respond to it. For example:</p><p> </p><p>Our Eight Point Plan for National Parks will:</p><ul><li>Double the number of apprenticeships in National Park Authorities by 2020;</li><li>Provide a new package of teaching materials for schools based on National Parks;</li><li>Engage directly with more than 60,000 young people a year through schools visits by 2017/18.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Defra has also worked closely with its delivery bodies and partners on a Natural Connections Pilot Project that supported schools, not only to connect children with nature through outdoor learning, but also to make sure schools are able to connect outdoor learning to their curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>We are also helping schools plant a million trees in their communities, so children can see first-hand the power of nature.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","905731","2016-07-07T15:05:42.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533487/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533487/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Wildlife","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans the Government has to help more children access and understand nature.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","905726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533488","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>Our farming and food sector need to draw from the widest possible range of talents, including women. A record 2600 women are now leading farms and am I keen to build on this, which is why I championed women’s involvement in farming at a recent round table.</p><p>There was significant growth in the take-up of agriculture as a degree course last year and it is encouraging that so many people are seeing the potential of this exciting career. More women than ever before are taking agriculture-related courses, with women now accounting for 62% of enrolments.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2016-07-07T16:47:38.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533488/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533488/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Agriculture: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she plans to take to encourage more women to work in the food and farming industries.","false","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher","905730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533489","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>As part of the Government’s funding agreement, Defra regularly assesses the performance of the National Wildlife Crime Unit.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, for example, as part of an international law enforcement operation, the Unit supported 28 investigations and supported seizures of almost 700 illegal goods derived from protected species.</p><p> </p><p>Defra and the Home Office have guaranteed funding for NWCU until March 2020.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-07T14:50:34.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533489/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533489/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Nature Conservation: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the National Wildlife Crime Unit in tackling wildlife crime and protecting endangered animals.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","905727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533490","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>The Government’s ambition is to connect more children with nature. We have supported a number of initiatives for children to access and better understand the environment. Our aim is to not only give all children the chance to experience the natural world, but also to understand it, and respond to it. For example:</p><p> </p><p>Our Eight Point Plan for National Parks will:</p><ul><li>Double the number of apprenticeships in National Park Authorities by 2020;</li><li>Provide a new package of teaching materials for schools based on National Parks;</li><li>Engage directly with more than 60,000 young people a year through schools visits by 2017/18.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Defra has also worked closely with its delivery bodies and partners on a Natural Connections Pilot Project that supported schools, not only to connect children with nature through outdoor learning, but also to make sure schools are able to connect outdoor learning to their curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>We are also helping schools plant a million trees in their communities, so children can see first-hand the power of nature.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","905726","2016-07-07T15:05:42.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533490/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533490/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Wildlife","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans the Government has to help more children access and understand nature.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","905731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533491","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>In 2014 Defra published independent research on the status of pollinators in the UK. This showed an overall decline in wild bee diversity, a major cause of which has been the loss of flower-rich habitat driven by changes in agricultural land use and urbanisation.</p><p> </p><p>Our National Pollinator Strategy highlights the vital contribution we can all make, from farmers to window box gardeners, to support pollinators by ensuring they have food and a home.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-07T16:13:39.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533491/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533491/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the reasons for the decline in the bee population.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","905729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533492","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-07","<p>All fresh milk served in government establishments and more than 90% of butter and cheese served is made from British milk. This represents £11 million of business for British dairy farmers.</p><p>We are working with all central Departments to ensure their food and catering contracts comply with the balanced scorecard approach.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice recently launched a tender for supplying food to prisons, worth £500m, which requires bids to use the balanced scorecard. From April this year all 30 million portions of UHT milk supplied to prisons each year is 100% British milk. We are working with MoD to develop the best way to embed the balanced scorecard into their forthcoming contracts for the Armed Forces at home and abroad.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2016-07-07T16:51:12.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533492/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533492/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-04","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress is being made on ensuring that government departments buy more British food.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","905732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531443","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government’s top priority for steel has not changed in the light of the EU referendum. The process for selling Tata Steel’s remaining UK assets remains ongoing and we continue to work closely with Tata and potential bidders so that we can secure a sustainable future.</p><p> </p><p>My officials have also met with parties interested in acquiring Tata’s steel pipe mills in Hartlepool, to explain what the Government is doing to support the UK steel sector.</p><p> </p><p>More widely, we are committed to working closely with the UK steel sector through the Steel Council.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-07-11T14:09:02.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531443/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531443/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531443/answer/previousversion/6035","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-01","Iron and Steel: Hartlepool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking in response to the result of the EU referendum to ensure that investment in the Hartlepool steel pipe mills is made.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","41624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531444","Department for International Trade","false","2016-08-26","<p>Until we have left the EU, the UK will remain a member of the EU with all of the rights and obligations that membership entails. In due course, Britain will be leaving the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. We recognise the need for a smooth transition which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. It would be wrong to set out unilateral positions at this stage. Already though we have seen expressions of interest in future trade deals with the United Kingdom, such as from the Prime Minister of Australia.</p><p> </p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2016-08-26T12:20:26.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531444/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531444/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-01","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the Government plans to meet with the (a) Australian, (b) New Zealand and (c) Canadian governments to discuss the potential effect on trade with those countries of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","41618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531445","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-05","<p>The Prime Minister announced during his statement to the House on the 27th June, the Cabinet will create a new EU unit in Whitehall, which will bring together officials and policy expertise from across the Cabinet Office, HM Treasury, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-05T10:00:12.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531445/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531445/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-01","Trade: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government plans to establish a Department for Trade.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","41617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531446","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-07","<p>An estimate is not possible because information on successive tenures of dwellings is not held centrally.</p><p>Under Right to Buy there are financial restrictions in place for re-sale within 5 years, and councils have the right of first refusal to buy back the property for up to 10 years at market value.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-07T16:34:25.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531446/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531446/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-01","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of local authority-owned properties which have been sold under the Right to Buy scheme and subsequently let by private landlords.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","41636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531447","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>I will be working closely with all of our sectors to make sure they have a voice as we now prepare for a negotiation to exit the EU.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","41598","2016-07-06T16:15:45.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531447/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531447/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has had discussions with his European counterparts on funding for the universal service obligation.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531448","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>I will be working closely with all of our sectors to make sure they have a voice as we now prepare for a negotiation to exit the EU.</p><p>Meanwhile, nothing changes - the UK remains a member of the EU and roaming charges will be abolished from 15 June 2017, in line with the Commission's timetable.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-06T16:17:16.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531448/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531448/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Mobile Phones: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what meetings he has had with mobile telephone providers on the implications of the outcome of the EU referendum for roaming charges; and what assessment he has made of whether roaming charges for UK citizens travelling in the EU will remain at their current level.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531449","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>I will be working closely with all of our sectors to make sure they have a voice as we now prepare for a negotiation to exit the EU.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","41596","2016-07-06T16:15:45.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531449/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531449/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Vodafone: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has met with representatives of Vodafone to discuss the implications of the outcome of the EU referendum for the location of its headquarters in London.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531450","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p><br>It will be for the Government, under the new Prime Minister, to begin negotiations to exit the EU.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-06T16:18:12.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531450/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531450/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department is making in respect of EU (a) Directives which are passed and not yet implemented and (b) Regulations which will be adopted before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531451","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister, and we have now got to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, Departments continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-06T16:19:25.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531451/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531451/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on implementation of the Digital Economy Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","41600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531452","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-07","<p>The recently published White Paper addresses concerns that were raised during our public consultation by the devolved nations and some English regions. The Government has made detailed proposals which ensure that the BBC is accountable to licence fee payers in all nations and regions in the UK through a clear focus on the BBC’s obligations in the new operating licence regime, clear board-level responsibilities, and a continued commitment to the out-of-London production targets.</p><p>Budgeting and commissioning decisions are editorial matters for the BBC.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-07T14:36:54.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531452/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531452/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-01","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of requiring at least 50 per cent of the licence fees raised in each region to be spent in that region on programme commissioning.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531453","Department for Education","false","2016-07-11","<p>Funding for education is a priority for this government. As announced at the Spending Review, we have protected the core schools budget in real terms. This year the schools budget will total around £40 billion. We are also committed to making funding fairer by introducing a national funding formula. A national funding formula will ensure that all schools are on an even starting point from which to build educational excellence. This is because a national funding formula will recognise pupil need, and pupils with similar needs will attract the same amount of funding wherever they are in the country.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-11T16:40:20.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531453/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531453/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-01","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department plans to publish a response to the finding of the National Union of Teachers survey, published in March 2016, that 70 per cent of school leaders believed that a lack of school funding was affecting education standards in their schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","41603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531454","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>Information about the number of pupils in Key Stage 1 classes with more than 30 pupils is available at school level in the underlying data of the ‘schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistics.[1]</p><p>In January 2016 there were 93 pupils in infant classes of more than 30 in schools in Ashfield constituency, and none in classes of more than 35.</p><p>In Nottinghamshire local authority there were 975 pupils in infant classes of more than 30, and none in classes of more than 35.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a> - data is located in the ‘underlying data’ download within the file called ‘SFR20_2016_Schools_Classes_UD’</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-06T15:44:26.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531454/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531454/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-01","Primary Education: Class Sizes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in Key Stage 1 in (a) Ashfield constituency and (b) Nottinghamshire were taught in classes of more than (i) 30 or (ii) 35 in the academic year beginning September 2015.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","41627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531455","Department for Education","false","2016-07-06","<p>The Department collects information from each local authority on the number of schools, the number of places in those schools and the number of pupils on roll through the annual School Capacity Survey (SCAP). The Department does not collect school capacity information at parliamentary constituency level. The data is published annually. Data relating to the position in the 2015/16 academic year will be collected over the coming months.</p><p>Data for May 2015 (relating to academic year 2014/15) can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-capacity-academic-year-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-capacity-academic-year-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>The Department does not collect capacity information specifically relating to the position at September, nor does it collect information on over-subscription.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-06T15:45:02.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531455/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531455/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-01","Primary Education: Class Sizes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which primary schools in (a) Ashfield constituency and (b) Nottinghamshire were were full or over capacity in the academic year beginning September (i) 2014 and (ii) 2015.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","41628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531456","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-06","<p>Until we leave the EU, current arrangements for farming, fisheries, food and drink and our environment remain in place.</p><p> </p><p>Defra will continue to ensure the right policies are in place for a cleaner, healthier environment for everyone. It is also vital that British farming is profitable and remains competitive – it is the bedrock of the food and drink industry, Britain’s largest manufacturing sector.</p><p> </p><p>The priorities for negotiating our exit from the EU will be a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","41632 ; 41633 ; 41634 ; 41635","2016-07-06T12:50:15.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531456/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531456/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-01","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) air pollution, (b) water pollution, (c) protection of species and habitats and (d) waste management.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","41631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531457","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-06","<p>Until we leave the EU, current arrangements for farming, fisheries, food and drink and our environment remain in place.</p><p> </p><p>Defra will continue to ensure the right policies are in place for a cleaner, healthier environment for everyone. It is also vital that British farming is profitable and remains competitive – it is the bedrock of the food and drink industry, Britain’s largest manufacturing sector.</p><p> </p><p>The priorities for negotiating our exit from the EU will be a matter for the new Prime Minister and their Cabinet.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","41631 ; 41633 ; 41634 ; 41635","2016-07-06T12:50:15.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531457/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/531457/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-01","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on food standards and food safety.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","41632"
